 early Morgenstern songs to his Lied-like setting of Brecht's 1939 "To Those Who Come After" and his treatment of Hölderlin's poetry in the 1940s Hollywood Songbook; the final two chapters focus on Eisler's Goethe settings in the early GDR, followed by his late Serious Songs recalling Brahms in their reflective approach. In its combination of textual and musicological analysis, this book balances technical and lay vocabulary to reach readers with or without musical background. The author's practical perspective as a singer also informs the book, as she addresses not only what Eisler asks of the voice but also the challenge of evoking both intimacy and distance in his politically fraught art songs. Heidi Hart holds a PhD in German Studies from Duke University. She is an instructor in the College of Humanities and Social Sciences at Utah State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSongsy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aGerman Literature. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh  aAesthetic Material.  aArt Songs.  aCreative.  aGerman Democratic Republic.  aHanns Eisler.  aIdeological Pressures.  aLieder Tradition.  aMusic.  aMusicological.  aPerformative.  aPolitical Agendas.  aPolitics.  aReflection.  aRhetorical.  aTextual Analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787442863?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787442863423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787442863/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles